Thanks a lot, and sorry for the delay!

My main comment is about wether we should put a uniform structure on `ContinuousMultilinearMap 𝕜 E F` if we only have a topology on `F`, the rest is pretty minor.

```suggestion
lemma toUniformOnFun_toFun [TopologicalSpace F] (f : ContinuousMultilinearMap 𝕜 E F) :
```

For some reason my instinct would be to only define the topology given `TopologicalSpace F` and then the uniform structure only if we have `UniformSpace F`. That's not really dangerous I believe, but I would say it's nicer to have the uniform structure defined in terms of the one available when there is one. I'm ready to be convinced otherwise though.

Note that it means that all lemmas involving only topology have to be stated in this setting, similarly to what is done for continuous linear maps.

I diverged from `ContinuousLinearMap` on purpose (and I was going to submit a PR changing `ContinuousLinearMap`s later): we don't have to worry about diamonds here; moreover, if `F` has canonical topology but no canonical uniformity, then we still can get a `UniformSpace` instance for continuous maps. TBH, I have no examples of vector spaces with a canonical topology but no canonical uniformity.

My concern is not diamond issues (as you said we don't have to worry about diamonds here), but rather about not having nice defeqs. I guess you could argue that the whole construction is too complicated to be able to rely on defeq, but still I would prefer if the uniformity on continuous linear maps was defined in terms of the uniformity on the codomain. If that's too annoying, I would rather have only the uniform setup (assuming uniform space directly).
Could you change `∀ i, E i` to `Π i, E i` in the whole file?
Other files about `ContinuousMultilinerMap`s use `∀ i, E i`.
I think this is only a remain of the switch to Lean4, when we had no `Π` notation. If you prefer to do the change in all these files at once that can also wait for a later PR of course.
I know the name is inspired by the current `continuous_eval_left`, but I think it would be more recognizable as `uniformContinuous_eval_const`.
